WEBVTT

00:00.917 --> 00:01.960
[TV static drones]

00:02.043 --> 00:04.879
[bright tone]

00:04.963 --> 00:07.799
[spirited orchestral music]

00:07.882 --> 00:15.015
♪ ♪

01:40.433 --> 01:43.228
[all chanting] Eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight, eight,

01:43.311 --> 01:45.979
eight, eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight!

01:46.064 --> 01:47.565
- I won't keep you all night!

01:47.607 --> 01:50.110
You have little enough time
of your own!

01:50.193 --> 01:52.445
That's right.
Eight, eight, eight!

01:52.529 --> 01:55.573
Eight hours of work,
eight hours of rest,

01:55.615 --> 01:56.658
and eight hours...

01:56.741 --> 01:58.618
all: For what you will!

01:58.702 --> 02:02.414
- Now, they'll be ready with
their patrols and their guns.

02:02.455 --> 02:04.290
We'll bring weapons of our own!

02:04.374 --> 02:08.002
- Yeah!
- No scabs will take our job!

02:08.086 --> 02:10.005
[all chanting]
Strike, strike, strike,

02:10.088 --> 02:14.551
strike, strike, strike, strike,
Strike, strike, strike, strike,

02:14.592 --> 02:16.136
strike, strike...

02:16.219 --> 02:17.554
- With the Wintertons
joining us--

02:17.595 --> 02:19.305
- And bringing
a host of friends.

02:19.389 --> 02:21.266
- I feel more confident
than ever

02:21.307 --> 02:24.102
that our new Metropolitan Opera
will be a great success.

02:24.185 --> 02:25.728
- This is good news.

02:25.770 --> 02:27.397
May I ask,
who are the friends you propose

02:27.439 --> 02:28.732
to bring over to our side?

02:28.773 --> 02:30.483
- The people you want,
but couldn't get,

02:30.567 --> 02:33.820
the Wilsons, the Marshalls,
the Webbs, and many others.

02:33.903 --> 02:35.030
- My.

02:35.113 --> 02:37.073
- Mr. Winterton can
be very persuasive.

02:37.115 --> 02:39.993
But there is one slight issue.

02:40.076 --> 02:42.037
- [chuckles]
Why am I not surprised?

02:42.120 --> 02:44.831
- The Wintertons have done us
such a great service in this.

02:44.914 --> 02:45.915
- Yes.

02:45.957 --> 02:49.753
- And they want the central box
in the first tier.

02:49.793 --> 02:51.963
[light music]

02:52.047 --> 02:53.214
- You mean my box?

02:53.298 --> 02:55.300
- Where else should we sit
when we've encouraged

02:55.383 --> 02:57.177
our friends
to leave the Academy?

02:57.260 --> 03:00.388
They'll expect us
to be in the central box.

03:00.472 --> 03:03.308
- We all want the Metropolitan
to be a success.

03:03.391 --> 03:04.684
Surely, we can agree on that.

03:04.768 --> 03:07.145
- And now it will be,
thanks to us.

03:07.187 --> 03:11.775
♪ ♪

03:11.816 --> 03:14.736
- This should take you
through the week.

03:14.819 --> 03:18.740
♪ ♪

03:18.823 --> 03:20.825
Just sign here.

03:20.867 --> 03:27.707
♪ ♪

03:35.840 --> 03:38.301
Sir?
- Ah.

03:38.343 --> 03:40.345
- Mr. Church.
He was drunk?

03:40.428 --> 03:43.264
- I wonder if Mr. Russell
knows that his butler

03:43.348 --> 03:45.308
goes out and gets drunk.

03:45.350 --> 03:47.018
- It's not our concern.

03:47.102 --> 03:48.520
- I don't agree.

03:48.603 --> 03:51.690
And I do not believe
that I can let it rest there.

03:51.731 --> 03:53.817
- Is it that stupid
letter again?

03:53.858 --> 03:56.653
He said he was sorry.
- He can say what he likes.

03:56.695 --> 03:57.696
He still wrote it.

03:57.737 --> 04:01.324
- So this is a chance
for revenge?

04:01.366 --> 04:03.785
- Is it revenge I seek?

04:03.868 --> 04:06.204
Or is it justice?

04:06.287 --> 04:08.248
That is the question.

04:08.331 --> 04:15.463
♪ ♪

04:17.757 --> 04:20.135
- Ah, Mr. Van Rhijn,
thank you for coming.

04:20.218 --> 04:22.387
I have your check right here.

04:22.429 --> 04:24.848
- Your note surprised me.

04:24.889 --> 04:27.600
I'm not sure I understand.

04:27.684 --> 04:30.145
- I have already told you
that the principals want

04:30.228 --> 04:32.355
to proceed
with as few investors

04:32.397 --> 04:33.398
in the partnership as possible.

04:33.440 --> 04:36.443
I was able to get you in,
but they're now insisting

04:36.526 --> 04:39.029
that we reduce our numbers,
and so they are paying

04:39.070 --> 04:42.115
a premium to buy out all
of the smaller stakeholders.

04:42.198 --> 04:45.702
I think you'll find you made
a good return in a short time.

04:52.375 --> 04:54.127
- Astonishing return.

04:54.210 --> 04:56.588
- I'm pleased
if you're pleased.

04:58.381 --> 05:00.592
- But suppose I don't want
to accept the check.

05:00.675 --> 05:02.594
How much would I have
to invest to be a principal

05:02.635 --> 05:04.512
and not a small stakeholder?

05:04.596 --> 05:07.432
- I don't know, Mr. Van Rhijn,
a great deal of money.

05:07.515 --> 05:09.517
My advice would be
to cash that check

05:09.601 --> 05:11.478
and enjoy the profits
you have made.

05:11.561 --> 05:13.980
- But if I don't cash it,
and I come back in two days

05:14.064 --> 05:16.941
with a great deal of money?

05:16.983 --> 05:20.362
- Mr. Van Rhijn, may I ask,

05:20.445 --> 05:23.448
is Miss Beaton aware
of any of this?

05:23.531 --> 05:25.784
- No, she would only try
to dissuade me,

05:25.867 --> 05:28.119
but please,
don't worry about that.

05:28.203 --> 05:31.748
I will tell her in good time
for us to celebrate together.

05:31.790 --> 05:38.797
♪ ♪

05:39.964 --> 05:42.509
- Is it dinner?
- Not quite, ma'am.

05:42.592 --> 05:44.886
I should have brought these up
earlier, but I forgot.

05:44.969 --> 05:47.347
It's the afternoon post.
It came when you were out.

05:47.430 --> 05:50.433
I am sorry.
- Never mind.

05:52.143 --> 05:54.145
[sighs]
- Who was that from?

05:54.187 --> 05:55.772
- Your Aunt Ada.

05:55.814 --> 05:59.025
No doubt bleating on
about her untold happiness.

05:59.109 --> 06:01.319
If only it were untold.

06:01.361 --> 06:04.072
- I think she is happy.

06:04.155 --> 06:05.824
- Oh, this is from Dashiell.

06:05.907 --> 06:08.618
He's giving a party to support
the botanical gardens.

06:08.660 --> 06:09.953
- That's good of him.

06:09.994 --> 06:11.871
- His family have been
patrons for years.

06:11.955 --> 06:14.499
But more to the point, he wants
you to be one of the guests.

06:14.582 --> 06:16.167
- Then why didn't
he write to me?

06:16.251 --> 06:18.253
- Well, I'm also invited.

06:18.336 --> 06:20.964
But clearly,
he is quite taken with you.

06:21.006 --> 06:24.175
- I know you think
Dashiell very suitable.

06:24.259 --> 06:26.553
- You must give me
some credit, Marian.

06:26.636 --> 06:28.388
I do not think he is suitable

06:28.471 --> 06:30.849
because he
is well-born and rich,

06:30.890 --> 06:33.852
but in addition
to those useful qualities,

06:33.935 --> 06:38.023
he is also intelligent
and very nice.

06:38.106 --> 06:39.691
He's even handsome.

06:39.733 --> 06:41.568
- What more could
a girl ask for?

06:41.651 --> 06:43.653
- I only mean
that you should consider it.

06:43.695 --> 06:45.655
- Aunt Ada said
something similar.

06:45.697 --> 06:46.865
- Really?

06:46.906 --> 06:50.118
As a rule,
realism is not her strong suit.

06:50.201 --> 06:51.536
- When is Dashiell's party?

06:51.619 --> 06:55.498
- The afternoon of the 21st.

06:55.540 --> 06:56.916
What's the matter?

06:57.000 --> 06:58.960
- That's the afternoon
I said I would

06:59.044 --> 07:00.295
teach Jane Addams' class.

07:00.378 --> 07:02.881
- Oh, you cannot be serious.

07:02.922 --> 07:05.425
You would miss it
to teach a bunch of indigents?

07:05.508 --> 07:07.552
How will painting
help them anyway?

07:07.594 --> 07:09.763
What are they to learn next?
Gilding?

07:09.846 --> 07:12.640
Lace making?
How to dive for pearls?

07:12.724 --> 07:14.476
- I'm teaching them
to read and write.

07:14.559 --> 07:16.061
- But why not teach
them the following day.

07:16.102 --> 07:19.189
They'll still be poor and needy
on the 22nd, I promise you.

07:19.230 --> 07:21.566
- What does Aunt Ada say?

07:21.649 --> 07:23.193
- What does she always say?

07:23.234 --> 07:25.403
She's wonderful,
he's wonderful,

07:25.487 --> 07:28.156
even the Niagara Falls
are wonderful.

07:28.239 --> 07:31.076
She seems rather limited
in her choice of adjectives.

07:31.117 --> 07:32.494
- Let her enjoy herself.

07:32.577 --> 07:33.912
And when they come
back to New York,

07:33.953 --> 07:37.916
please be kind to them,
for all our sakes.

07:37.957 --> 07:39.793
- It is hard to be kind
when he has taken

07:39.876 --> 07:41.586
advantage of her innocence.

07:41.670 --> 07:44.673
- I think
good will come from it.

07:44.756 --> 07:47.175
- Good came
from the American Revolution,

07:47.258 --> 07:50.095
but it was difficult
to live through all the same.

07:50.136 --> 07:52.597
♪ ♪

07:52.681 --> 07:54.599
- I can't even imagine
the danger you were in.

07:54.641 --> 07:55.892
They might have killed you.

07:55.933 --> 07:58.770
- I believe
that was their intention.

07:58.853 --> 08:01.106
- How was Mr. Fortune
through it all?

08:01.189 --> 08:02.774
- Brave.

08:02.816 --> 08:05.985
Braver than I was.
He stood up to them.

08:06.069 --> 08:08.238
That was what got us
into trouble.

08:08.279 --> 08:11.074
- It's quite a story,
trembling all night in a barn,

08:11.116 --> 08:14.869
listening to a ravening mob
hurtling by.

08:14.953 --> 08:17.288
I imagine
it brought you closer.

08:19.290 --> 08:21.084
- He kissed me.
- What?

08:21.126 --> 08:24.754
When?
- In the barn.

08:24.796 --> 08:26.715
We were frightened
for our lives,

08:26.798 --> 08:28.800
hiding, huddled together.

08:28.842 --> 08:30.760
- But he's married.
- I know!

08:30.802 --> 08:33.138
- Of course you do.
I'm sorry.

08:33.179 --> 08:36.558
- It was wrong and foolish.

08:37.558 --> 08:41.312
But the truth is,
he's a friend now.

08:41.354 --> 08:43.940
I can talk to him
about anything.

08:43.982 --> 08:45.650
Even my son.

08:45.692 --> 08:49.404
He understands,
and he challenges me.

08:49.487 --> 08:51.990
He champions my work.

08:53.324 --> 08:55.076
- You mean
you're in love with him?

08:55.160 --> 08:57.454
- I'm sorry?
- That's what it sounds like.

08:57.495 --> 09:00.165
And I don't want you
to be hurt.

09:00.206 --> 09:02.500
- It's too late for that.

09:02.584 --> 09:04.669
The only thing
we both know for certain

09:04.753 --> 09:07.505
is that I'm going to get hurt.

09:07.589 --> 09:10.508
[clock ticking]

09:10.550 --> 09:16.097
♪ ♪

09:16.181 --> 09:19.059
[alarm ringing]

09:19.142 --> 09:26.066
♪ ♪

09:35.200 --> 09:37.243
- 6:00 on the dot.

09:37.327 --> 09:38.703
I really think I cracked it.

09:38.787 --> 09:40.580
- I knew you would
if you didn't give up.

09:40.663 --> 09:42.832
- Yes, well done, Jack.

09:42.874 --> 09:46.211
- It's a real achievement.
- I'm so pleased for you.

09:46.252 --> 09:48.546
- Might I ask for the stairs
to be brushed

09:48.630 --> 09:49.798
and the rug put straight?

09:49.881 --> 09:51.341
I nearly tripped coming down.

09:51.383 --> 09:52.842
- Never mind that now.

09:52.884 --> 09:54.886
What will you do next, Jack?

09:54.928 --> 09:56.846
- What do you think
he should do, Mr. Bannister?

09:56.888 --> 09:59.557
- Well, if you're serious, and
the clock really does work--

09:59.599 --> 10:01.309
- It does, Mr. Bannister.

10:01.393 --> 10:04.437
- And you've invented a new
element that makes it work.

10:04.521 --> 10:06.022
- A lot was just servicing it,

10:06.064 --> 10:08.566
but I have made a new kind
of escape wheel.

10:08.608 --> 10:09.901
You can't buy one like it.

10:09.984 --> 10:12.028
- Oh, well,
you're talking double Dutch,

10:12.070 --> 10:13.697
but I'd say you should
apply for a patent

10:13.738 --> 10:15.281
to protect your invention.

10:15.365 --> 10:16.574
- Could I do that?

10:16.658 --> 10:17.826
- You'd have
to ride to Washington

10:17.909 --> 10:19.577
or go to a government office
here in New York.

10:19.661 --> 10:21.246
- They'll have to check
that no one else

10:21.287 --> 10:22.414
has invented the same thing.

10:22.497 --> 10:23.665
- That's it.

10:23.748 --> 10:26.751
Then they'll tell you if your
application's been successful.

10:26.793 --> 10:28.128
- But how much would it cost?

10:28.211 --> 10:31.631
- Oh, I know about this
because I had a friend

10:31.715 --> 10:33.758
who tried for a patent
and failed.

10:33.842 --> 10:36.219
The charge is $15
when you apply...

10:36.261 --> 10:37.053
- [inhales sharply]

10:37.095 --> 10:40.432
- And $20 more
if they grant it.

10:40.515 --> 10:42.058
- I'll have to wait
and save it up.

10:42.100 --> 10:43.435
- You can't wait.

10:43.476 --> 10:45.103
Someone else
may beat you to it.

10:45.145 --> 10:47.439
- I've got $2.
You'll take it.

10:47.480 --> 10:49.524
- Oh, no, I couldn't.

10:49.607 --> 10:51.026
- You can have 4 from me.

10:51.109 --> 10:53.611
- And I've got 4.
- I could give you 1.

10:53.653 --> 10:54.946
- Miss Marian
will want to add some.

10:55.030 --> 10:56.781
- Yes.
- You'll have what you need.

10:56.823 --> 10:58.533
- You'll get nothing from me.

10:58.616 --> 11:01.619
I work too hard
to waste it on moonshine.

11:01.703 --> 11:05.457
- You can go on Thursday.
I'll tell Mrs. Van Rhijn.

11:05.540 --> 11:08.918
- What if you pay the money,
and they refuse the patent?

11:08.960 --> 11:11.171
Do you get the money back?

11:11.254 --> 11:12.339
- I don't know.

11:12.422 --> 11:15.300
- You let us worry about that.

11:15.383 --> 11:17.135
- Thank you.

11:17.177 --> 11:20.805
Thanks to all of you.
I'll never forget this, never.

11:20.847 --> 11:23.558
- Go and make us proud.

11:23.641 --> 11:26.519
♪ ♪

11:26.603 --> 11:28.063
- Did anyone lay a hand on you?

11:28.146 --> 11:30.148
- No, because they
didn't find us.

11:30.190 --> 11:32.067
- I wish you would've talked
to me about the South

11:32.150 --> 11:32.942
before you left.

11:32.984 --> 11:34.527
- Mother tried to warn me.

11:34.611 --> 11:37.655
I'm not sure I fully believed
her then, but I do now.

11:37.697 --> 11:39.991
- I'm just grateful
that God protected you.

11:40.033 --> 11:41.534
- I wanted you
to hear it from me

11:41.618 --> 11:42.994
because the article
about our trip

11:43.078 --> 11:44.204
is coming out in "The Globe."

11:44.287 --> 11:46.998
- I thought you were there
just to write about the school?

11:47.040 --> 11:49.501
- We've covered that,
but we had to set down

11:49.584 --> 11:50.752
what we'd seen as well.

11:50.835 --> 11:52.712
- I don't want you
doing any more stories

11:52.796 --> 11:54.172
that put you in harm's way.

11:54.255 --> 11:55.674
- How could I know
what would happen?

11:55.715 --> 11:56.716
- I would have.

11:56.800 --> 11:59.135
It's typical for Alabama.

11:59.177 --> 12:01.346
A woman should not have a job
that could get her killed.

12:01.388 --> 12:03.848
- So you'd rather
I just sat in your pharmacy

12:03.890 --> 12:05.850
and did nothing
with my skills to help

12:05.892 --> 12:07.352
better the world in some way?

12:07.394 --> 12:10.188
- That's not what I'm saying.
- We just want you to be safe.

12:10.271 --> 12:12.524
- Well, you can't always
keep your children safe.

12:12.565 --> 12:14.067
You know that.

12:17.112 --> 12:19.656
I only wanted to alert you
about the article,

12:19.698 --> 12:21.741
not start a war.

12:21.825 --> 12:25.245
- I'm glad
you're telling their stories.

12:25.328 --> 12:28.707
Education and training is
the way forward for our people.

12:28.790 --> 12:31.459
- And they are doing
their level best to stop us.

12:31.543 --> 12:32.961
Even here in New York.

12:33.044 --> 12:35.213
You should write about that.
- About what?

12:35.296 --> 12:37.382
- The Education Board
is trying to close down

12:37.465 --> 12:40.176
the colored schools,
including Mrs. Sarah Garnet's.

12:40.218 --> 12:41.886
- Where you play piano?
- Yes.

12:41.970 --> 12:44.222
And more importantly,
where Sarah is principal.

12:44.305 --> 12:47.809
If they prevail, the students
won't go to school,

12:47.892 --> 12:50.645
while Sarah and the other
teachers have no work.

12:50.729 --> 12:51.896
- Well, that's shameful.

12:51.980 --> 12:53.481
What reason do
they give for the closure?

12:53.565 --> 12:55.191
- As if they need one.

12:55.233 --> 12:57.777
But they say the colored
teachers are inferior.

12:57.861 --> 12:59.988
- The lies
they tell themselves.

13:00.071 --> 13:01.489
They have to be stopped.

13:01.573 --> 13:03.408
- Well, if you'd like to help,

13:03.491 --> 13:06.327
I was about to leave
for a meeting at Sarah's shop.

13:06.411 --> 13:07.704
- I'll come with you.

13:07.746 --> 13:09.789
- All right,
I'll get my things.

13:09.873 --> 13:11.583
♪ ♪

13:11.666 --> 13:13.460
- When will you be coming home?

13:13.543 --> 13:15.295
- I don't know.

13:15.378 --> 13:20.467
♪ ♪

13:20.550 --> 13:22.218
- My dear.

13:22.260 --> 13:26.806
♪ ♪

13:26.890 --> 13:31.353
- I know it's silly,
but I feel rather nervous.

13:31.436 --> 13:32.979
- No need.

13:33.063 --> 13:34.773
You're an independent
married woman,

13:34.856 --> 13:38.109
fully the equal
of Mrs. Van Rhijn.

13:38.193 --> 13:40.111
- Of course.

13:40.153 --> 13:43.323
But I'm not sure Agnes
will quite see that.

13:43.406 --> 13:49.746
♪ ♪

13:49.788 --> 13:52.540
- The Niagara Falls
were really wonderful.

13:52.624 --> 13:54.709
So much more impressive
than in the photograph.

13:54.793 --> 13:57.796
- Yes, so you said
in your letters.

13:57.879 --> 14:00.006
- We've settled
into the rectory,

14:00.090 --> 14:03.093
and Pumpkin seems
quite happy there.

14:03.176 --> 14:05.637
- Settled?

14:05.679 --> 14:08.348
When did you get home?

14:08.431 --> 14:10.016
- Monday evening.

14:10.100 --> 14:12.811
But I wanted to unpack
and get things back to normal

14:12.852 --> 14:14.354
before we came to visit.

14:14.437 --> 14:16.189
- I see.

14:18.233 --> 14:19.859
- May I fetch you
some more coffee?

14:19.943 --> 14:20.902
- Oh, yes, thank--
- [grunts]

14:20.985 --> 14:22.862
- Is something wrong?

14:22.946 --> 14:25.156
- Alas, I suffer
from a bad back,

14:25.240 --> 14:26.908
like too many
of my parishioners.

14:26.991 --> 14:28.868
- I'm afraid I made it worse.

14:28.952 --> 14:31.413
Luke carried me
across the threshold.

14:31.496 --> 14:33.039
- By night, I hope.

14:33.123 --> 14:36.710
It's not exactly an image
for public consumption.

14:36.793 --> 14:39.045
- I do want you
to go see the doctor.

14:39.129 --> 14:40.839
- But there's
nothing to be done.

14:40.880 --> 14:43.049
- Oh, there must be something.
Do sit down.

14:43.133 --> 14:45.135
I'll ring for John.

14:45.176 --> 14:49.806
And I'll ask him to call on
Dr. Lewis to come and see you.

14:49.848 --> 14:53.184
- I suppose Marian is teaching,
or else she'd be here with us.

14:53.226 --> 14:55.645
- This teaching nonsense
has taken over her life.

14:55.687 --> 14:57.272
- It's not nonsense, Agnes.

14:57.355 --> 14:59.524
- She has promised some
do-gooder that she would teach

14:59.566 --> 15:03.028
some class of beggars to read
and write on the evening

15:03.111 --> 15:04.779
of cousin Dashiell's party.

15:04.863 --> 15:06.406
- For which
she deserves our praise.

15:06.489 --> 15:08.700
- Oh, she cannot miss
Dashiell's party for them.

15:08.783 --> 15:09.993
What does she think?

15:10.035 --> 15:12.203
That their social diaries
will prevent them

15:12.245 --> 15:13.496
from changing the date?

15:13.538 --> 15:16.041
- She takes her commitment
to the poor seriously.

15:16.082 --> 15:17.375
Jesus teaches--

15:17.459 --> 15:19.669
- Even Jesus would
understand that she

15:19.711 --> 15:21.546
cannot turn down
a potential suitor

15:21.588 --> 15:23.715
for a bunch of hobbledehoys.

15:23.757 --> 15:25.800
- I'm not sure he would.

15:25.884 --> 15:27.761
- [chuckles]

15:27.844 --> 15:30.263
- You were kind
to bring her home.

15:30.347 --> 15:32.599
I meant for you
to put her in a cab.

15:32.682 --> 15:34.684
- I like to walk.

15:34.726 --> 15:36.186
- Is the carriage mended yet?

15:36.227 --> 15:38.688
- It will be tomorrow.

15:38.730 --> 15:41.024
♪ ♪

15:41.066 --> 15:42.734
- Is that your wife?

15:42.776 --> 15:46.237
- Yes, that's Harriet.

15:46.279 --> 15:50.158
- It's so nice to have
it there as a reminder.

15:50.241 --> 15:53.912
- Well, I don't need reminding.

15:53.953 --> 15:56.915
- Will they have our portraits
at the botanical gardens too?

15:56.998 --> 16:00.669
- No, that will just be
a plaque with our names.

16:00.710 --> 16:02.253
And the names
of my parents too.

16:02.337 --> 16:03.463
- How nice.

16:03.546 --> 16:06.132
- Our family sponsored
the new solarium.

16:06.216 --> 16:07.759
- I'm so sorry
to have to miss it.

16:07.842 --> 16:09.469
- What?

16:09.552 --> 16:12.138
Don't say that. Why?

16:12.222 --> 16:15.141
- I'm taking an evening class
to teach the basic skills

16:15.225 --> 16:17.185
needed to find work.

16:17.268 --> 16:19.646
Reading, writing, you know,
that sort of thing.

16:19.729 --> 16:21.189
- This is for poor people?

16:21.272 --> 16:22.982
- Yes, and that's the date.

16:23.066 --> 16:24.859
- Couldn't you change it?

16:24.943 --> 16:27.028
- Please.

16:27.112 --> 16:29.239
It won't be the same
without you there.

16:29.280 --> 16:31.282
- I'm afraid I can't be.

16:31.366 --> 16:34.119
The school asked me to take
the lesson, and I said yes.

16:34.202 --> 16:35.995
- But you don't have
to do what they tell you.

16:36.079 --> 16:38.707
It's not as if
you're a real teacher.

16:40.165 --> 16:42.127
- I wish you would reconsider.

16:42.210 --> 16:45.338
I don't think
the poor people would mind.

16:45.422 --> 16:46.756
- [chuckles]

16:46.798 --> 16:53.763
♪ ♪

16:55.640 --> 16:58.977
- In short,
we must work together.

16:59.019 --> 17:00.478
Please join us
in showing your support

17:00.520 --> 17:04.398
by signing the petition
to stop the board.

17:04.482 --> 17:05.858
Thank you.

17:05.942 --> 17:08.819
[applause]

17:08.903 --> 17:13.116
♪ ♪

17:13.157 --> 17:15.076
- Look who I brought.

17:15.160 --> 17:17.328
- Aren't you a sight
for sore eyes?

17:17.369 --> 17:19.204
- It's so nice
to see you again.

17:19.289 --> 17:21.583
But I'm sorry it's
under these circumstances.

17:21.665 --> 17:23.042
- I am as well.

17:23.126 --> 17:25.587
- If you stay determined,
they won't win.

17:25.670 --> 17:27.130
- It's an uphill battle.

17:27.172 --> 17:29.632
Some of the teachers are
already looking for new jobs.

17:29.674 --> 17:32.385
I have the seamstress shop,
but that won't be enough

17:32.469 --> 17:33.970
to make a living
if the schools close.

17:34.054 --> 17:36.222
- Organizing this meeting
is a good first step.

17:36.306 --> 17:37.682
- But it's not enough.

17:37.766 --> 17:41.227
- You know, Peggy has
an important piece coming out

17:41.311 --> 17:43.188
in "The Globe"
about Booker T. Washington's

17:43.271 --> 17:44.731
school in Tuskegee.

17:44.814 --> 17:46.024
- Mother.

17:46.066 --> 17:47.776
- I was just thinking,

17:47.817 --> 17:50.612
this could be
your next article.

17:50.695 --> 17:53.448
First, she wrote
about education in the South,

17:53.531 --> 17:56.409
but we face our own challenges
here in the North.

17:56.493 --> 18:00.288
- That's exactly what we need,
public exposure.

18:00.372 --> 18:02.874
Some folks don't even know
this is happening.

18:02.957 --> 18:05.168
We need parents,
and colored businesses,

18:05.210 --> 18:08.171
and the press
to fight this together.

18:08.213 --> 18:09.673
- What do you say?

18:09.714 --> 18:11.633
- It does sound
like something my editor

18:11.716 --> 18:13.301
would be interested in.

18:13.385 --> 18:16.680
But I have to speak
with him first.

18:16.721 --> 18:19.724
- Whatever you can do, Peggy,
we'd be most appreciative.

18:19.808 --> 18:22.060
- Well, I think your editor
is going to be interested.

18:22.102 --> 18:23.395
- I think so as well.

18:23.478 --> 18:25.105
- So could you
move the Mansfields

18:25.188 --> 18:26.564
to the 10th, please?

18:26.606 --> 18:28.650
And send a thank you letter
to the governor.

18:28.733 --> 18:29.734
- Of course.

18:29.818 --> 18:31.903
- You cannot know how happy
I am to have you back,

18:31.945 --> 18:33.697
Miss Scott.

18:33.738 --> 18:37.325
John, what is this business
Bannister has been

18:37.409 --> 18:40.495
telling me about a clock?

18:40.578 --> 18:42.706
- John's invented
a type of alarm clock.

18:42.747 --> 18:46.418
He's applying for a patent.
- How exciting.

18:46.459 --> 18:50.171
We all rely on alarm clocks,
and most of them don't work.

18:50.255 --> 18:52.716
- I rely on Armstrong.
- Who always sets an alarm.

18:52.757 --> 18:54.968
- We've all chipped in
downstairs for John

18:55.051 --> 18:56.052
to pay the patent fee.

18:56.094 --> 18:59.097
- Well, then we
must contribute.

18:59.139 --> 19:00.849
- I think I got enough money.

19:00.932 --> 19:03.101
- No one has enough money.

19:03.184 --> 19:04.978
Here are $5.

19:05.061 --> 19:07.188
- And I'll give you 3.

19:07.272 --> 19:09.107
- But Miss Armstrong asked
would I pay back

19:09.149 --> 19:10.900
the money if they don't
give me the patent,

19:10.942 --> 19:12.152
and I'm not sure I could.

19:12.235 --> 19:14.070
- Never mind Armstrong.

19:14.112 --> 19:17.198
I like the idea
of supporting an inventor.

19:17.282 --> 19:19.784
And now we must
go up and change.

19:19.868 --> 19:23.621
♪ ♪

19:23.705 --> 19:25.665
- People can surprise you,
can't they?

19:25.749 --> 19:27.542
- They believe in you.

19:27.625 --> 19:29.502
And so do I.

19:29.586 --> 19:36.217
♪ ♪

19:36.301 --> 19:38.053
- Why did you come
to New York?

19:38.136 --> 19:40.388
- There was more
possibilities over here.

19:40.472 --> 19:42.182
- Are you proficient
in hairstyling?

19:42.265 --> 19:43.725
- I did my own today.

19:43.808 --> 19:46.144
Women have their hair done
for the gentlemen.

19:46.186 --> 19:48.688
Don't you agree, Mr. Church?

19:48.772 --> 19:51.816
- And Mrs. Wagner would
give you a reference?

19:51.900 --> 19:53.234
- Not Mrs. Wagner, no.

19:53.318 --> 19:54.652
She's dead.

19:54.736 --> 19:57.864
- All work and no play
makes Jack a dull boy.

19:57.947 --> 20:00.241
- And I was sick of London.

20:00.325 --> 20:02.285
- Wouldn't you say so,
Mr. Church?

20:02.327 --> 20:04.746
- I think we've heard enough.

20:04.829 --> 20:08.333
We'll let you know.
- You have my address.

20:08.416 --> 20:10.293
I hope you'll be the one
to write to me.

20:10.335 --> 20:12.212
- Can you find your way out?

20:12.295 --> 20:15.507
- [scoffs]
If I have to.

20:15.548 --> 20:19.636
♪ ♪

20:19.678 --> 20:21.054
- No.
- No.

20:21.137 --> 20:22.347
[horse whinnies]

20:22.389 --> 20:23.682
- Might I make a suggestion?

20:23.723 --> 20:28.186
I could come for a trial
of a week or a month,

20:28.269 --> 20:30.689
with no obligation
on either side.

20:30.730 --> 20:34.776
Then Mrs. Russell would have
time to make up her mind.

20:34.859 --> 20:36.528
- Very sensible.

20:36.611 --> 20:39.030
- Then I think
that is everything.

20:39.114 --> 20:40.323
♪ ♪

20:40.365 --> 20:42.534
I will bid you good day.

20:42.575 --> 20:45.412
♪ ♪

20:45.495 --> 20:47.914
- I would say
our search is done.

20:47.997 --> 20:49.624
- Most definitely.

20:49.708 --> 20:51.376
♪ ♪

20:51.459 --> 20:53.545
- Pinkerton's men say
the worker's resolve

20:53.586 --> 20:54.963
is stronger than ever
and they'll fight

20:55.046 --> 20:56.214
if it comes to it.

20:56.297 --> 20:58.299
- Mr. Russell.
- I'll be with you in a moment.

20:58.383 --> 21:00.218
Could you give
Mr. Gilbert some coffee?

21:00.260 --> 21:01.511
- Go on.

21:01.553 --> 21:02.887
- They barricaded
the mills and the river.

21:02.929 --> 21:04.806
The governor will send
the National Guard,

21:04.889 --> 21:07.434
and the scab labor's
ready to take over.

21:07.517 --> 21:09.561
- Will we have trouble
getting them inside?

21:09.644 --> 21:12.313
- We'll have troops
here and here

21:12.397 --> 21:13.898
to escort them
through the gates.

21:13.982 --> 21:16.192
- So you think you can get
the scabs into the mills?

21:16.234 --> 21:17.402
- I can guarantee.

21:17.485 --> 21:19.195
- There are no
guarantees in war.

21:19.237 --> 21:21.114
And that's what this is.

21:21.197 --> 21:22.824
As you yourself have said.

21:22.907 --> 21:24.701
And now, Mr. Gilbert,
you've been very patient.

21:24.743 --> 21:26.077
- Of course, sir.

21:26.161 --> 21:27.454
It's some time since I've been

21:27.537 --> 21:28.663
in a railroad car
as fine as this.

21:28.747 --> 21:30.582
- You can see I'm rather busy.

21:30.623 --> 21:32.542
And I'm on my way
to Pittsburgh, so perhaps,

21:32.584 --> 21:34.544
I should cut straight to
my reasons for asking you here.

21:34.586 --> 21:35.378
- Good.

21:35.420 --> 21:36.421
- Mrs. Russell tells me

21:36.463 --> 21:37.714
that Mr.
and Mrs. Joshua Winterton

21:37.756 --> 21:39.257
have abandoned the Academy
and come to you.

21:39.341 --> 21:40.383
- They have.

21:40.425 --> 21:43.762
I don't really know why,
but it is quite a coup for us.

21:43.803 --> 21:44.888
- Just so.

21:44.929 --> 21:47.140
And I gather Mrs. Winterton
has requested the very box

21:47.223 --> 21:48.433
that was earmarked for my wife.

21:48.475 --> 21:49.726
- Mrs. Russell has

21:49.768 --> 21:51.603
very graciously agreed
to step aside.

21:51.644 --> 21:54.230
- Ah, now,
that is what cannot happen.

21:54.272 --> 21:55.690
- I'm sorry.
Is the train moving?

21:55.774 --> 21:57.734
- On the opening night,
Mrs. Russell will preside

21:57.776 --> 21:59.361
from the central box
in the first tier.

21:59.444 --> 22:01.780
- But I've already--
- A memory test for you.

22:01.821 --> 22:04.449
Some time ago,
work stopped on the upper house

22:04.532 --> 22:06.076
because you ran out of money.

22:06.117 --> 22:08.161
When and why did it
start again?

22:08.244 --> 22:09.621
- Because you signed a check.

22:09.662 --> 22:11.831
But Mrs. Russell
was not to be told.

22:11.915 --> 22:13.625
- And now you have
a similar conundrum.

22:13.667 --> 22:15.460
Mrs. Russell will
have her box back,

22:15.502 --> 22:17.087
but neither she
nor Mrs. Winterton

22:17.128 --> 22:19.798
needs to be aware of this
before the opening night.

22:19.839 --> 22:21.299
- But the Wintertons
are difficult.

22:21.341 --> 22:22.842
What if I can't arrange it?

22:22.926 --> 22:26.137
- Then I will demand the debt
is repaid at once and in full.

22:26.179 --> 22:27.639
- The whole debt?

22:27.722 --> 22:30.642
- For which you
yourself have signed.

22:30.725 --> 22:33.895
Now, I'm afraid
I must get back to my work.

22:33.978 --> 22:35.480
Good day, Mr. Gilbert.

22:35.563 --> 22:36.940
- But the train's
left the station.

22:36.981 --> 22:39.651
- You can ride with us
to Middleton and get off there.

22:39.734 --> 22:41.111
Take a seat.

22:41.152 --> 22:48.118
♪ ♪

22:55.000 --> 22:57.377
- Oh, I saw the doctor
for my back.

22:57.460 --> 22:59.504
He gave me some liniment.
- Good.

22:59.587 --> 23:01.006
- He's looking
into one or two things,

23:01.047 --> 23:03.508
but he seems to think
I'm in reasonably good shape.

23:03.591 --> 23:05.593
- Will there be anything else?

23:05.677 --> 23:07.679
- I don't think so, no.

23:07.721 --> 23:09.514
Unless you want some cheese?

23:09.556 --> 23:11.182
- No, thank you.

23:12.892 --> 23:16.396
- What do you mean,
he's looking into some things?

23:16.479 --> 23:18.356
- There's nothing
to worry about.

23:18.398 --> 23:21.443
["Blue Danube" playing]

23:21.526 --> 23:23.236
- What is that?

23:23.319 --> 23:25.864
- That is
our very own music box.

23:25.947 --> 23:27.490
- What?
- [laughs]

23:27.532 --> 23:29.159
- It sounds so loud.

23:29.200 --> 23:31.536
It must be a very grand one.

23:31.578 --> 23:33.413
- A parishioner gave it
to us as a wedding present.

23:33.496 --> 23:36.291
I asked Sally to turn it on.

23:36.374 --> 23:38.293
- It's playing
the "Blue Danube."

23:38.376 --> 23:40.211
- Mm-hmm.

23:40.253 --> 23:46.134
♪ ♪

23:46.217 --> 23:48.053
Come dance with me.

23:48.136 --> 23:55.101
♪ ♪

23:56.895 --> 24:00.231
- You make me feel
as if I were 16 again.

24:00.273 --> 24:02.567
Is that good?

24:02.609 --> 24:04.319
- It feels good to me.

24:04.402 --> 24:11.534
♪ ♪

24:30.095 --> 24:32.097
- Hello.

24:32.138 --> 24:33.640
- Where are you coming from?

24:33.723 --> 24:36.434
- I stood in line all afternoon
at a government office

24:36.518 --> 24:38.603
to try to get a patent
for my invention.

24:38.687 --> 24:40.605
I'm sorry I haven't
been around lately.

24:40.647 --> 24:42.023
- Thought you'd gone off me.

24:42.107 --> 24:44.776
- I spent all my spare time
working on my clock.

24:44.859 --> 24:46.403
- Were you successful
with the patent?

24:46.444 --> 24:48.446
- I don't know yet.

24:48.488 --> 24:50.824
- We had a business
here the other night.

24:50.907 --> 24:53.743
Mr. Church went out
and came home drunk.

24:53.785 --> 24:55.578
Apparently, it was
the 30th anniversary

24:55.620 --> 24:57.038
of his wife's death.

24:57.122 --> 25:00.375
She died of smallpox
on her 24th birthday.

25:00.458 --> 25:02.919
- That's very sad.
- I know.

25:02.961 --> 25:05.463
I may not be here much longer.
- Why not?

25:05.505 --> 25:07.298
- They're interviewing
for a new lady's maid.

25:07.340 --> 25:08.550
- Have they given
you any notice?

25:08.633 --> 25:09.801
- Not yet.

25:09.884 --> 25:11.928
I'm supposed to look
after Miss Gladys again.

25:11.970 --> 25:13.972
- But haven't you always
been her maid too?

25:14.014 --> 25:17.308
- It's a demotion,
whatever you say.

25:17.392 --> 25:19.686
All right, I better go in.

25:19.769 --> 25:23.523
- If you do leave,
will you tell me?

25:23.606 --> 25:25.316
- Good luck with the patent.

25:25.400 --> 25:28.319
[light music]

25:28.361 --> 25:30.155
♪ ♪

25:30.196 --> 25:31.865
- You're back, good.

25:31.948 --> 25:34.159
I thought I might have
to serve dinner alone.

25:34.200 --> 25:35.618
- Tell us all about it.

25:35.660 --> 25:37.287
- There's nothing to tell.

25:37.328 --> 25:40.707
I stood in line, I filled in
the forms, paid the fee.

25:40.790 --> 25:42.625
Now I just have to wait.

25:42.667 --> 25:44.044
I saw Miss Weber in the street.

25:44.127 --> 25:47.130
She told me that Mr. Church
went out the other night

25:47.172 --> 25:48.506
and came back drunk.

25:48.548 --> 25:50.675
- Mr. Church, the butler?

25:50.717 --> 25:52.344
I find that hard to believe.

25:52.385 --> 25:55.180
- It was the 30th anniversary
of his wife's death.

25:55.221 --> 25:56.639
- Oh, that's awful.

25:56.681 --> 26:00.101
- That must have been
the smallpox outbreak of '53.

26:00.185 --> 26:02.687
- It was.
She was 24.

26:02.771 --> 26:05.482
- Mr. Bannister,
might I have a word?

26:05.523 --> 26:10.695
♪ ♪

26:10.737 --> 26:12.864
I hope you'll let it go now.

26:12.906 --> 26:15.033
Mr. Church has been
through enough.

26:15.075 --> 26:17.827
- I would,
but I've already written.

26:17.869 --> 26:19.454
I delivered it last night.

26:19.537 --> 26:22.874
- Well, you must do something.

26:22.916 --> 26:26.044
♪ ♪

26:26.086 --> 26:28.421
- Did you get my message?
- I did.

26:28.505 --> 26:31.925
You're very persistent,
Mr. Van Rhijn.

26:32.008 --> 26:34.552
♪ ♪

26:34.636 --> 26:36.304
- I have the money.

26:36.388 --> 26:37.722
- I might as well tell you

26:37.806 --> 26:41.351
that I'm not comfortable
about this.

26:41.393 --> 26:43.978
I'm not comfortable at all.

26:44.062 --> 26:45.689
- Why not?

26:45.730 --> 26:48.900
- Miss Beaton may appear
to be witty and sophisticated,

26:48.983 --> 26:51.486
but the truth is,
she's an innocent.

26:51.569 --> 26:53.238
She has always been protected--

26:53.321 --> 26:56.700
- By her father, Mr. Gould?
- Never mind that.

26:56.741 --> 27:00.537
It's enough to say she does
not deserve to be used.

27:00.578 --> 27:02.580
- But I'm not using her.

27:02.664 --> 27:04.165
I swear to you that she
will enjoy the benefits

27:04.249 --> 27:05.917
of this transaction
as much as I will.

27:06.001 --> 27:09.587
I mean to make her happy,
Mr. Crowther.

27:09.671 --> 27:12.007
Truly, I do.

27:12.090 --> 27:16.678
♪ ♪

27:16.761 --> 27:18.513
- So be it.

27:18.596 --> 27:25.729
♪ ♪

27:29.190 --> 27:31.067
- You didn't have
to wait in the street.

27:31.109 --> 27:33.903
- I wanted some air,
and it's a lovely afternoon.

27:33.945 --> 27:36.406
- Yes, Dashiell's been lucky.

27:36.448 --> 27:39.200
- I'm looking forward to it.

27:39.284 --> 27:41.202
- Miss Beaton.

27:41.286 --> 27:45.540
♪ ♪

27:45.623 --> 27:48.209
- We're going
to Mr. Montgomery's party.

27:49.544 --> 27:52.630
Mother, are you listening?

27:52.672 --> 27:54.591
- Is that from father?
How's he getting on?

27:54.632 --> 27:56.718
- It's from
the Duke of Buckingham.

27:56.801 --> 27:58.094
- What does he want?

27:58.136 --> 28:00.263
- He confirms that he's
coming to New York City

28:00.305 --> 28:02.390
for the opera opening night.

28:02.474 --> 28:04.267
- And that's good, is it?

28:04.309 --> 28:05.602
- Don't be such a child.

28:05.643 --> 28:07.103
Of course it's good.

28:07.145 --> 28:08.730
It's wonderful.

28:08.813 --> 28:10.774
I will have an English Duke
as the guest of honor

28:10.815 --> 28:12.942
in my box on the opening night,
and I very much doubt

28:12.984 --> 28:15.987
Mrs. Astor can say the same.

28:16.029 --> 28:18.281
In fact, I'm going to send
a note to Mr. McAllister

28:18.323 --> 28:21.451
to tempt him to join
our party and abandon hers.

28:21.493 --> 28:22.994
- I don't understand.

28:23.036 --> 28:25.330
Are you and Mrs. Astor
friends or rivals?

28:25.372 --> 28:27.123
- The two are not exclusive.

28:27.165 --> 28:34.172
♪ ♪

28:36.091 --> 28:38.301
- I don't really understand
why you asked to see me,

28:38.343 --> 28:39.886
Dr. Sanders.

28:39.969 --> 28:43.848
Dr. Murphy gave me a salve
that seems to be working.

28:43.932 --> 28:47.018
- I'm afraid
Dr. Murphy's analysis

28:47.102 --> 28:50.980
suggested other possibilities.

28:51.022 --> 28:55.527
He asked my advice
because I have more experience

28:55.610 --> 28:58.530
with this condition.

28:58.571 --> 29:01.408
- What, bad backs?

29:01.491 --> 29:06.246
♪ ♪

29:06.329 --> 29:10.208
- Try to remember
that reading is a key,

29:10.250 --> 29:14.254
and it will unlock your life
if only you'll let it.

29:16.089 --> 29:18.299
Oh, Miss Frost, may I help?

29:18.383 --> 29:19.968
- Aren't you going
to the party being given

29:20.051 --> 29:21.720
by Frances Montgomery's father?

29:21.761 --> 29:23.805
I'm sure she said
you've been invited.

29:23.888 --> 29:26.266
- That doesn't matter.
- Nonsense.

29:26.349 --> 29:27.642
You can't miss it.

29:27.726 --> 29:29.477
I heard it's going
to be splendid.

29:29.561 --> 29:31.479
I'll take over here.

29:31.563 --> 29:33.481
- I don't know.
- Go.

29:33.565 --> 29:35.942
We'll see you next week.

29:40.530 --> 29:43.158
All right, who's next?

29:43.199 --> 29:46.119
[sweeping music]

29:46.202 --> 29:53.126
♪ ♪

29:55.795 --> 29:58.256
- How splendid this is.

29:58.298 --> 30:00.675
Marian will be furious
with herself

30:00.759 --> 30:02.802
when she hears
what she's missed.

30:02.886 --> 30:05.430
- That's good of you.

30:05.513 --> 30:07.682
- Oh, no.

30:07.766 --> 30:09.225
Larry!

30:09.267 --> 30:11.353
- Hello, Mr. Russell.
- Hello.

30:11.436 --> 30:13.063
- Miss Russell.

30:13.104 --> 30:15.190
- He seems keen.
Who is he?

30:15.273 --> 30:16.441
- Anthony Grace.

30:16.524 --> 30:18.276
- Another suitor?
- You joke.

30:18.318 --> 30:20.320
He's been stalking me
at every ball I go to.

30:20.403 --> 30:23.239
- Well, you are a debutante.
You're an heiress.

30:23.323 --> 30:24.616
What did you expect?

30:24.657 --> 30:27.160
- I didn't quite understand
it would be open season.

30:27.243 --> 30:28.411
- Nonsense.

30:28.453 --> 30:30.914
They are the hunters,
and you're the prey.

30:30.955 --> 30:33.291
Just fend them off
until you find the right one.

30:33.333 --> 30:35.627
- It's exhausting.

30:35.669 --> 30:36.836
- At least
you won't have to worry

30:36.920 --> 30:39.172
about Oscar van Rhijn anymore.

30:39.255 --> 30:41.633
- I'm happy for
Mr. Van Rhijn and Miss Beaton.

30:41.716 --> 30:44.219
I've met her.
She's nice.

30:46.096 --> 30:48.515
- You're in a very sunny mood.

30:48.598 --> 30:51.101
- I feel sunny.

30:51.142 --> 30:54.187
Things are going well.

30:54.270 --> 30:56.439
Or is it a risk to say that?

30:56.481 --> 30:59.150
- Even if it is, you are
not afraid of taking a risk,

30:59.192 --> 31:00.318
are you?

31:00.360 --> 31:02.904
- Certainly not.

31:02.987 --> 31:04.823
- [laughs]

31:04.864 --> 31:07.784
[light music]

31:07.826 --> 31:15.166
♪ ♪

31:15.959 --> 31:18.420
- Really, Mr. Van Rhijn,
isn't this the moment

31:18.503 --> 31:20.922
when I slap you
and walk off in a huff?

31:21.006 --> 31:23.883
- Not in our version
of the story.

31:23.967 --> 31:26.261
- Oh, there you are.

31:26.344 --> 31:28.471
♪ ♪

31:28.513 --> 31:30.140
You've found me.

31:30.181 --> 31:31.975
- Hasn't Dashiell
done things well?

31:32.017 --> 31:33.643
- It's lovely.

31:33.685 --> 31:36.730
♪ ♪

31:36.813 --> 31:38.481
- Are you fond of flowers,
Aunt Agnes?

31:38.523 --> 31:39.983
- Very fond.

31:40.025 --> 31:42.360
As long as someone else
has grown them.

31:43.611 --> 31:45.989
- Oh, look!

31:46.031 --> 31:47.991
- I hope it's all right
that I came.

31:48.033 --> 31:49.367
- It's more than all right.

31:49.451 --> 31:51.911
- We're very pleased
to see you, my dear.

31:51.995 --> 31:53.580
Aren't we, Dashiell?

31:53.663 --> 31:55.415
- I can certainly say I am.

31:55.498 --> 32:01.838
♪ ♪

32:01.880 --> 32:04.090
- Mr. Bannister.

32:04.174 --> 32:05.884
What can I do for you?

32:05.967 --> 32:08.553
- I hope that you will
forgive this intrusion,

32:08.595 --> 32:13.058
but I wonder, has Mr. Russell
read his mail today?

32:13.099 --> 32:14.976
- Mr. Russell is in Pittsburgh.

32:15.060 --> 32:16.353
- Why do you ask?

32:16.394 --> 32:18.730
- A letter was delivered
by hand last night,

32:18.813 --> 32:22.776
and I'm anxious to get it back.

32:22.859 --> 32:25.028
- I don't think
I can allow that.

32:25.070 --> 32:28.907
- I see that I must
ask it as a favor.

32:28.948 --> 32:33.578
But first, might I explain?

32:33.620 --> 32:35.246
- Very well.

32:35.288 --> 32:41.544
♪ ♪

32:41.586 --> 32:44.589
- As you may have guessed,
I wrote the letter myself,

32:44.673 --> 32:46.508
and now I regret it.

32:46.591 --> 32:48.259
- Why did you write it?

32:48.301 --> 32:51.262
- To complain
about the behavior

32:51.304 --> 32:53.264
of Mrs. Russell
in the opera war.

32:53.348 --> 32:55.350
It's been upsetting
Mrs. Van Rhijn,

32:55.433 --> 32:57.852
and I asked
Mr. Russell to exercise

32:57.936 --> 32:59.646
control over his wife.

32:59.729 --> 33:02.190
- How on Earth did you think
you could write

33:02.273 --> 33:03.733
such a thing to Mr. Russell?

33:03.817 --> 33:05.860
If he sees it,
you'll lose your job.

33:05.944 --> 33:09.114
And this time,
it won't be my fault.

33:09.197 --> 33:12.450
- I can't explain it.

33:12.534 --> 33:15.745
I must have been mad.

33:15.787 --> 33:18.540
Of course, you'll think
I deserve whatever happens,

33:18.623 --> 33:20.542
and I don't blame you.

33:20.625 --> 33:27.549
♪ ♪

33:29.259 --> 33:30.593
- These are
the master's letters.

33:30.635 --> 33:32.303
Normally, they're
collected in the morning,

33:32.387 --> 33:35.974
but his secretary, Mr. Clay,
is with him in Pittsburgh.

33:36.057 --> 33:38.059
- That's it. Thank you.

33:38.143 --> 33:41.021
I must confess,
it's quite a relief.

33:41.104 --> 33:42.939
- I'm tempted to ask
if I can read it,

33:42.981 --> 33:44.399
given everything you've said.

33:44.482 --> 33:48.486
- If you'll forgive me,
I prefer to spare my blushes.

33:48.570 --> 33:51.489
♪ ♪

33:51.573 --> 33:53.908
Good day, Mr. Church.

33:53.992 --> 33:57.245
♪ ♪

33:57.328 --> 33:59.789
- I think Oscar is going
to surprise us all,

33:59.831 --> 34:02.042
and I couldn't be happier.

34:02.125 --> 34:03.668
- Do you mean what
I think you mean?

34:03.710 --> 34:06.254
- My lips are sealed.
It must come from him.

34:06.338 --> 34:09.007
- Oh, there you are.
Father sent me to find you.

34:09.049 --> 34:10.967
It's about to begin.

34:11.009 --> 34:13.844
♪ ♪

34:13.887 --> 34:16.431
- Can you manage it?
- Yes, yes.

34:16.514 --> 34:19.309
- This is quite a to-do
for the unveiling of a plaque.

34:19.351 --> 34:22.728
- Ah, There's Miss Brook.

34:22.812 --> 34:25.565
- Oh, what is it?

34:25.648 --> 34:32.530
♪ ♪

34:32.572 --> 34:35.992
- I moved back to New York
to see Frances settled

34:36.034 --> 34:40.038
in my old hometown,
but to my surprise,

34:40.121 --> 34:43.708
fate had plans for me too.

34:43.750 --> 34:48.713
I never thought I'd find
someone else to love,

34:48.755 --> 34:53.885
to stand by my side,
to care for my daughter

34:53.967 --> 34:56.679
as if she were her own.

34:56.721 --> 34:59.683
We are here to celebrate
what my family has done

34:59.724 --> 35:00.975
for the botanical gardens,

35:01.059 --> 35:04.270
but my family
is not yet complete.

35:04.354 --> 35:08.108
I realized that soon
after I met Miss Brook.

35:08.191 --> 35:10.318
Many of you here
are friends of Miss Brook,

35:10.402 --> 35:13.363
and may have been puzzled
by my invitation.

35:13.405 --> 35:17.283
The truth is, I have
invited you to witness this.

35:24.624 --> 35:30.088
Marian Brook,
will you marry me?

35:30.130 --> 35:31.923
- Bravo.

35:33.508 --> 35:35.468
- She hasn't accepted him yet.

35:35.552 --> 35:37.178
- She will.

35:39.014 --> 35:40.890
- Is Aunt Agnes right?

35:40.932 --> 35:42.600
Will you?

35:48.023 --> 35:50.942
[soft music]

35:51.026 --> 35:54.946
♪ ♪

35:55.030 --> 35:56.990
- If you really want me to.

35:57.073 --> 35:59.951
[crowd exclaiming]

36:00.035 --> 36:02.954
[applause]

36:03.038 --> 36:05.790
♪ ♪

36:05.874 --> 36:07.709
- Wow.

36:07.792 --> 36:10.211
♪ ♪

36:10.295 --> 36:13.965
- Dashiell,
well done, well done.

36:14.007 --> 36:16.926
- I have to go.
I have to pack.

36:16.968 --> 36:18.803
- I'll see you
when you get back.

36:18.845 --> 36:20.722
- I'd like to think so.

36:20.805 --> 36:27.604
♪ ♪

36:27.645 --> 36:29.564
- Congratulations.

36:29.647 --> 36:32.317
♪ ♪

36:32.400 --> 36:34.861
- It's just hard to relive.

36:34.944 --> 36:37.113
♪ ♪

36:37.155 --> 36:39.616
I have a lead on another story.

36:39.657 --> 36:42.285
My mother is a friend
of Sarah Garnet,

36:42.327 --> 36:44.204
principal of one
of the three colored schools.

36:44.287 --> 36:46.164
- Yeah, I know who she is.

36:46.206 --> 36:47.582
- Well, she says
that the Board of Education

36:47.665 --> 36:50.168
is trying to close all
of the schools, including hers.

36:50.251 --> 36:51.920
- I heard that was the plan,
but I never thought

36:52.003 --> 36:53.296
they'd go through with it.

36:53.338 --> 36:55.131
- They've been smearing
the colored teachers

36:55.173 --> 36:57.884
and saying
that the schools are badly run.

36:57.967 --> 36:59.177
Can't we expose them?

36:59.219 --> 37:01.221
- We can, and we will.

37:01.304 --> 37:03.640
But first, we must
rally the community.

37:03.682 --> 37:06.309
- Mrs. Garnet said
we needed you in this fight.

37:06.351 --> 37:07.477
She was right.

37:07.519 --> 37:09.604
- We can start
on that tomorrow.

37:11.398 --> 37:13.441
- Is that wise?

37:13.525 --> 37:14.526
- What do you mean?

37:14.567 --> 37:17.445
- Only that we wrote
the Tuskegee article together.

37:17.529 --> 37:20.031
Maybe another journalist
should cover the story.

37:20.073 --> 37:22.659
- You brought me the idea.
Don't you want to write it?

37:22.701 --> 37:24.369
- I just wonder
what it looks like

37:24.452 --> 37:26.579
if we write
everything together.

37:26.663 --> 37:29.541
- It looks and it reads
like good journalism.

37:29.582 --> 37:31.710
First, we need
to speak to the teachers.

37:31.793 --> 37:33.211
- I can start that.

37:33.294 --> 37:34.629
But it's late.

37:34.713 --> 37:36.673
Your family must
be expecting you.

37:36.715 --> 37:38.299
- I don't like
leaving you alone.

37:38.383 --> 37:40.719
- Why?
I can finish and close up.

37:43.138 --> 37:45.015
- Whoa!
- Don't get out.

37:45.056 --> 37:46.558
You can wait for me here.

37:46.641 --> 37:49.936
- If you insist on doing this,
then I'm coming with you.

37:50.020 --> 37:52.647
- No, I'll go in alone.

37:52.731 --> 37:56.234
- If I had the power,
I'd forbid it.

37:56.317 --> 37:58.194
- But you don't
have that power.

37:58.236 --> 38:01.156
[tense music]

38:01.239 --> 38:08.371
♪ ♪

38:19.341 --> 38:21.801
- Please, sit down.

38:21.885 --> 38:23.261
- Thank you.

38:23.345 --> 38:25.555
- I'm surprised
you'd come here.

38:25.597 --> 38:28.975
- Why not?
You came to my house.

38:29.059 --> 38:33.772
And now, I hope we can find
a way out of this situation.

38:33.855 --> 38:36.149
- We cannot offer you
the hospitality you showed

38:36.232 --> 38:38.234
my husband, Mr. Russell,
but perhaps,

38:38.276 --> 38:39.527
you'll have some coffee.

38:39.611 --> 38:41.821
- Thank you.
You're very kind.

38:44.115 --> 38:46.326
I know you're a proud man,

38:46.409 --> 38:48.286
and I do not
hold it against you.

38:48.328 --> 38:50.330
I've come quite a distance too,

38:50.413 --> 38:52.624
and I'm proud
of the company I've built.

38:52.665 --> 38:54.876
Like you, I'll fight for it.

38:54.959 --> 38:56.336
- I am proud.

38:56.419 --> 38:58.254
I'm proud of my work
and my family.

38:58.296 --> 39:00.507
And my job is to protect them.

39:00.590 --> 39:03.176
We need the union
to do right by our families.

39:03.259 --> 39:05.261
- But if it comes to violence,

39:05.303 --> 39:07.681
no one wins,
and everyone suffers.

39:07.764 --> 39:09.307
- Your workers
are already suffering.

39:09.349 --> 39:10.809
They have no life.

39:10.850 --> 39:14.104
They work 10, 12, 14 hours
a day, six days a week,

39:14.145 --> 39:15.313
for which they're
paid barely enough

39:15.355 --> 39:16.690
to put food on the table.

39:16.773 --> 39:18.900
Your horses have better
treatment by far.

39:18.983 --> 39:20.694
- We offered a raised
to your tradesmen.

39:20.777 --> 39:23.571
- And they refused because we
won't be divided, as you know.

39:23.655 --> 39:25.949
- I cannot pay a different
basic rate for common labor

39:25.990 --> 39:27.992
without disrupting steel
production across the state,

39:28.076 --> 39:29.160
across all of America.

39:29.244 --> 39:30.453
- And that's your last word.

39:30.495 --> 39:31.830
- My last word on pay.

39:31.871 --> 39:34.374
On safety, even welfare,
there may be more

39:34.457 --> 39:35.667
to talk about, but not on pay.

39:35.750 --> 39:37.335
- Then there is
nothing more to say.

39:37.419 --> 39:40.171
- There is no point to this.

39:40.213 --> 39:42.132
The union funds
will soon run dry,

39:42.173 --> 39:44.050
and I will starve you out.

39:45.593 --> 39:47.137
- The men will do
what they must to stop

39:47.178 --> 39:49.556
scabs from taking our jobs.

39:49.639 --> 39:51.474
Some of them will get hurt.
Some may die.

39:51.516 --> 39:53.393
Doesn't that trouble you?

39:55.687 --> 39:57.772
- The stakes are high
for all of us.

40:01.735 --> 40:03.778
I hope it doesn't
come to violence.

40:03.862 --> 40:06.114
But we're prepared if it does.

40:08.450 --> 40:09.701
- That's good.

40:09.784 --> 40:11.286
- I'm leaving now,
Mrs. Henderson.

40:11.369 --> 40:13.413
But I want to thank you
for my coffee.

40:13.496 --> 40:15.874
- This is Mr. Russell.
He owns the mills.

40:15.915 --> 40:18.168
- I've started
at the mill myself, sir.

40:18.209 --> 40:20.003
My shift begins in an hour.

40:21.379 --> 40:23.548
- I'm sure
we're glad to have you.

40:23.590 --> 40:25.925
- I hope you find a way
to settle things, sir,

40:26.009 --> 40:27.927
for all our sakes.

40:28.011 --> 40:31.681
- I'm afraid I have not been
able to persuade your husband.

40:31.723 --> 40:34.392
- He only tries to do his best.

40:34.434 --> 40:36.436
- I would claim the same.

40:36.519 --> 40:37.896
But I've held up
your children's luncheon

40:37.979 --> 40:39.481
long enough.

40:39.564 --> 40:41.232
Good day to you.

40:41.274 --> 40:44.194
[soft music]

40:44.235 --> 40:51.201
♪ ♪

40:53.286 --> 40:56.414
- The strike affects
the whole town.

40:56.498 --> 40:58.833
- My mills employ
the whole town.

40:58.917 --> 41:00.585
- Exactly.

41:00.627 --> 41:03.672
We don't have a choice.
We have to work to survive.

41:03.755 --> 41:06.007
- Which is why you've made
your son work in a place

41:06.091 --> 41:07.842
where he's treated worse
than a horse.

41:07.926 --> 41:09.761
- This fight
is for all our sons

41:09.803 --> 41:13.098
to have something better.

41:13.181 --> 41:15.058
- I see.

41:16.476 --> 41:19.396
Thank you for your hospitality.
- Yeah.

41:19.437 --> 41:26.611
♪ ♪

41:35.704 --> 41:38.331
- What will you do now?

41:38.415 --> 41:41.251
- What can I do?
Bring them out on strike.

41:42.627 --> 41:44.379
May God help us all.

41:44.462 --> 41:48.591
♪ ♪

41:48.633 --> 41:52.512
- They'll take them
out today, or soon.

41:52.595 --> 41:54.097
He has nothing
to gain by giving us

41:54.139 --> 41:55.557
more time to prepare.

41:55.640 --> 41:57.475
- I'll cable the governor
and make sure

41:57.517 --> 41:59.894
of our new workforce.

41:59.978 --> 42:03.606
- His wife was there,
and his children.

42:03.648 --> 42:06.151
I'm surprised
they were not at school.

42:06.192 --> 42:08.319
♪ ♪

42:08.403 --> 42:10.238
Is there a school?

42:10.321 --> 42:12.532
- I neither know nor care.

42:12.615 --> 42:19.748
♪ ♪

42:28.131 --> 42:30.008
- One for you today.

42:33.887 --> 42:36.306
Aren't you going to open it?

42:36.348 --> 42:38.558
- I will when I'm ready.

42:45.815 --> 42:47.859
- To what do I owe
this pleasant surprise?

42:47.901 --> 42:49.652
- If only it were pleasant.

42:49.694 --> 42:53.406
- I'm afraid we have a serious
problem, Mrs. Van Rhijn.

42:53.490 --> 42:55.950
- Please, do sit down.

42:55.992 --> 42:58.912
[light music]

42:58.995 --> 43:01.706
♪ ♪

43:01.748 --> 43:03.625
What is the urgency?

43:03.708 --> 43:05.710
- Apparently,
a couple of the old guard

43:05.752 --> 43:07.879
have already been lured
away from the Academy

43:07.962 --> 43:10.965
to join the Wintertons
at the Metropolitan.

43:11.049 --> 43:14.219
I'm afraid others
will soon follow.

43:14.302 --> 43:15.845
- That's not all.

43:15.887 --> 43:18.723
The Duke of Buckingham has
agreed to be Mrs. Russell's

43:18.807 --> 43:21.685
guest of honor at the opening.

43:21.726 --> 43:25.480
He will hear
the opera from her box.

43:25.563 --> 43:27.399
- And the world will know it.

43:27.482 --> 43:29.109
- So what can we do?

43:29.192 --> 43:30.860
What can we do?

43:30.902 --> 43:33.988
- I don't know, Lina, but you'd
better think of something.

43:36.574 --> 43:38.243
- You.

43:38.326 --> 43:39.452
You know him.

43:39.536 --> 43:41.121
You've dined with him.

43:41.204 --> 43:44.290
Get him to ditch her and come
to the Academy instead.

43:44.374 --> 43:46.292
- What? How?

43:46.376 --> 43:48.545
- Find out what
she's offered and double it.

43:48.586 --> 43:51.423
Treble it if you must.
Btu get him.

43:51.464 --> 43:54.551
- Lina, you cannot buy a duke.

43:54.592 --> 43:56.594
- Just watch me.

43:56.678 --> 43:59.556
- I'll do my best,
but if I fail--

43:59.597 --> 44:01.016
- You won't.

44:01.099 --> 44:02.559
You can't.

44:02.600 --> 44:05.562
- Even if I succeed,
it may not be enough.

44:05.603 --> 44:07.439
- I don't think
I want to hear this.

44:07.522 --> 44:11.359
- Agnes, what else
is there to be done?

44:12.777 --> 44:15.780
- We need a two-fold attack.

44:15.822 --> 44:18.116
I will try to sway the duke,

44:18.158 --> 44:20.493
but you try to find
another trick up your sleeve

44:20.577 --> 44:22.787
to deal with Mrs. Russell.

44:22.871 --> 44:26.708
That is, if you want to win.

44:28.126 --> 44:30.628
- I'm glad you got it back,
but please,

44:30.712 --> 44:32.380
don't ever write another.

44:32.464 --> 44:35.216
- I know.
I won't write another.

44:35.300 --> 44:37.761
That's all done with now.

44:37.802 --> 44:41.681
Oh, have you finished
laying the luncheon?

44:44.559 --> 44:46.144
- Are you all right?

44:46.227 --> 44:49.105
You've been
in a funny mood all morning.

44:49.147 --> 44:52.025
- I got my letter
from the patent office.

44:56.154 --> 44:57.864
They said my work
cannot be considered

44:57.947 --> 45:00.367
since I don't belong
to a horological

45:00.450 --> 45:03.161
institute or society.

45:03.244 --> 45:04.996
- Well, I'm glad someone
with common sense

45:05.038 --> 45:07.165
finally joined the chorus.

45:07.248 --> 45:09.376
What is "horororogical"?

45:09.459 --> 45:11.461
- Clockmakers.

45:11.503 --> 45:13.254
- So that's that then.

45:13.338 --> 45:16.966
- Now, not so fast, lad.
Don't give up quite yet.

45:17.008 --> 45:18.968
- I knew it was
too good to be true.

45:19.010 --> 45:22.222
- Sanity returns
to 61st Street.

45:25.809 --> 45:29.187
♪ ♪

45:29.270 --> 45:31.690
- Can't he just join one
of those "horororo"

45:31.773 --> 45:33.858
whatever it is clubs?

45:33.900 --> 45:36.027
- I'm afraid
he needs certificates

45:36.111 --> 45:38.738
and qualifications
he hasn't got.

45:38.822 --> 45:41.408
- Is there any way around it?

45:41.491 --> 45:48.415
♪ ♪

45:50.583 --> 45:53.294
- Marian.
- I expected your summons.

45:53.378 --> 45:56.131
I hope you think
I've done the right thing.

45:56.214 --> 45:58.174
- You're talking
about Dashiell?

45:58.216 --> 46:00.719
- You said yourself
he has all the gifts

46:00.760 --> 46:02.053
the sensible woman could want.

46:02.095 --> 46:05.890
- Yes, but I
didn't send for you.

46:05.974 --> 46:07.225
- But Uncle Luke wrote--

46:07.267 --> 46:11.062
- I wrote that we needed you
to come, and we do.

46:13.064 --> 46:15.150
I saw another doctor.

46:15.233 --> 46:17.027
He came here.

46:17.068 --> 46:19.112
I have more than a bad back.

46:19.195 --> 46:22.866
And I wanted Marion here
with us when I told you.

46:22.907 --> 46:25.035
- Told me what?

46:26.036 --> 46:28.580
- First, I think
we should all sit down.

46:31.082 --> 46:34.085
Come, Ada, sit next to me.

46:40.175 --> 46:42.761
- Pay no mind
to Miss Armstrong.

46:42.802 --> 46:44.429
What does she know anyway?

46:44.471 --> 46:47.932
You're doing something none
of us could ever imagine.

46:47.974 --> 46:50.518
So keep at it.

46:50.602 --> 46:53.438
Promise.
- I promise.

46:54.689 --> 46:56.483
I guess.

46:56.566 --> 47:03.531
♪ ♪

47:06.034 --> 47:08.370
- Are they quite sure?

47:08.453 --> 47:11.623
- I'm afraid so.

47:11.664 --> 47:13.375
He has cancer.

47:13.458 --> 47:15.126
- Oh.
- Oh.

47:15.210 --> 47:17.921
- But how can that be?
He was here the other day.

47:17.962 --> 47:20.215
The only thing wrong
with him was a bad back.

47:20.298 --> 47:22.592
- This one starts
with a bad back,

47:22.634 --> 47:25.637
and then it spreads.

47:25.679 --> 47:27.806
He's seen two doctors.

47:27.889 --> 47:30.058
- I must look after Ada.

47:30.141 --> 47:32.936
Marian, please, ask Bannister
to fetch me a cab,

47:32.977 --> 47:37.315
and have Armstrong come
and get me ready to go out.

47:37.357 --> 47:40.777
- Poor Aunt Ada.
She doesn't have much luck.

47:40.819 --> 47:43.738
[soft music]

47:43.822 --> 47:50.954
♪ ♪

47:53.957 --> 47:56.251
- Come and lie down beside me.

48:08.179 --> 48:10.557
- We're going
to get through this.

48:12.058 --> 48:14.185
Who knows, maybe one day,

48:14.227 --> 48:16.813
you'll be sharing your miracle
from the pulpit.

48:16.855 --> 48:24.029
♪ ♪

48:24.821 --> 48:26.448
[bell chimes]

48:46.259 --> 48:48.553
Oh.

48:48.636 --> 48:51.598
[crying]

48:55.393 --> 48:57.645
- I'm here.

48:57.729 --> 48:59.898
I'm here,
and you're not to worry.

48:59.939 --> 49:07.113
♪ ♪

49:10.408 --> 49:13.912
- Mr. Bannister,
is everything all right?

49:13.995 --> 49:16.247
- I'm expecting
Mrs. Van Rhijn at any moment.

49:16.289 --> 49:18.166
We're to have an invalid
in the house,

49:18.249 --> 49:20.126
and she's bringing him.

49:20.210 --> 49:22.379
- Sorry to hear that.

49:23.880 --> 49:25.924
- Mr. Church, a while ago,

49:25.965 --> 49:28.176
you asked me to forget
our little contretemps

49:28.259 --> 49:31.054
that time when you got me into
trouble with Mrs. Van Rhijn.

49:31.096 --> 49:32.180
- I remember.

49:32.263 --> 49:34.933
You didn't think it was within
your power to forgive me.

49:35.016 --> 49:36.518
- I was wrong.

49:36.601 --> 49:41.481
For me, at least,
it is all forgotten entirely.

49:41.564 --> 49:48.488
♪ ♪

49:58.289 --> 50:01.167
- But where's Uncle Luke?
- They wouldn't come.

50:01.251 --> 50:03.753
Nothing I said
would persuade them.

50:03.837 --> 50:06.131
And now I'm going up.
I'm exhausted.

50:06.172 --> 50:07.799
Bannister,
would you tell Armstrong?

50:07.841 --> 50:10.135
- Of course, ma'am.

50:10.176 --> 50:13.680
- John, tell Mrs. Bauer
I'll have a tray in my room.

50:13.763 --> 50:15.640
- What's happening?

50:17.267 --> 50:20.270
- My aunt's husband
has been taken ill.

50:20.311 --> 50:23.440
And we hoped we could nurse
him here, but it seems not.

50:23.481 --> 50:25.025
- I am sorry,

50:25.108 --> 50:27.402
especially when you ought
to be celebrating.

50:27.485 --> 50:28.987
- Why?

50:29.029 --> 50:31.448
- Because you're engaged.

50:31.489 --> 50:34.367
- Oh.
[laughs]

50:35.493 --> 50:36.661
Oh, yes.

50:36.745 --> 50:40.290
This news has rather
driven that out of my head.

50:40.331 --> 50:42.834
- Please let me be of help.

50:42.876 --> 50:45.420
- Thank you.
I'll remember that.

50:52.135 --> 50:55.180
[people shouting in distance]

50:58.600 --> 51:00.185
- What's he saying?

51:00.268 --> 51:01.644
- The strikers
are still blocking

51:01.686 --> 51:03.188
the gates against the scabs.

51:03.229 --> 51:04.481
They won't let them
in the mills,

51:04.522 --> 51:06.358
but he's confident the guard
can have them inside

51:06.399 --> 51:07.484
and working before too long.

51:07.525 --> 51:09.652
- How long?
- Within the hour.

51:09.694 --> 51:12.739
- And the strikers can go home
and nurse their bruises.

51:12.822 --> 51:15.533
[gunshots]

51:15.617 --> 51:16.868
- I must get down there.

51:16.910 --> 51:18.370
- That is exactly
what you can't do.

51:18.453 --> 51:20.372
- I'm not staying here
if they're using guns.

51:20.455 --> 51:22.123
Take me
to the commanding officer.

51:22.207 --> 51:23.416
- Sir, it's not safe.

51:23.500 --> 51:25.043
- Do you think I'm going
to sit in an office

51:25.085 --> 51:26.961
while my mills go up in flames?

51:27.045 --> 51:29.464
Take me there now.
- Yes, sir.

51:31.049 --> 51:34.010
[all chanting] Eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight, eight,

51:34.052 --> 51:36.513
eight, eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight,

51:36.554 --> 51:39.265
eight, eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight,

51:39.349 --> 51:42.227
eight, eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight,

51:42.310 --> 51:45.021
eight, eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight,

51:45.063 --> 51:47.315
eight, eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight,

51:47.399 --> 51:50.193
eight, eight, eight...

51:50.235 --> 51:53.863
- On behalf of these men,
I ask you to leave.

51:53.905 --> 51:56.908
If you stay,
there will be bloodshed.

51:56.950 --> 51:59.077
I beg you, go.

51:59.119 --> 52:00.662
Eight, eight, eight!

52:00.745 --> 52:03.748
[all chanting] Eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight, eight,

52:03.832 --> 52:04.916
eight, eight, eight...

52:05.000 --> 52:06.126
- What were those shots?

52:06.209 --> 52:07.669
- Please go back
into the building, sir.

52:07.752 --> 52:08.920
Go back, all of you.

52:08.962 --> 52:10.046
It's not safe
for you to be here.

52:10.088 --> 52:12.257
- I am George Russell.
These are my mills.

52:12.340 --> 52:13.591
And I demand to know
what's happening.

52:13.675 --> 52:16.511
- They were warning shots.
No one was hurt.

52:16.594 --> 52:18.054
One moment, sir.

52:18.096 --> 52:19.931
[all chanting] Eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight, eight...

52:20.015 --> 52:21.725
- [shushing]

52:21.766 --> 52:24.644
- We're here to clear
the way for the new workers

52:24.728 --> 52:27.480
to get the mills
back into production.

52:27.564 --> 52:32.444
We have no wish to shed blood,
but we shall do so.

52:32.485 --> 52:36.781
We will mow every one
of you down if we must.

52:39.242 --> 52:41.661
You have one minute
to clear the way.

52:46.166 --> 52:47.709
- Eight, eight, eight!

52:47.792 --> 52:49.127
[all chanting]
Eight, eight, eight...

52:49.210 --> 52:51.171
- Captain,
ready the troops to fire.

52:51.254 --> 52:52.672
[all chanting]
Eight, eight, eight...

52:52.756 --> 52:54.549
- Company, load!

52:54.632 --> 52:57.177
[all chanting] Eight, eight,
eight, eight, eight, eight,

52:57.260 --> 52:58.470
eight, eight, eight...

52:58.511 --> 53:00.555
- Son, come here, come here.

53:00.638 --> 53:02.432
Workmen!

53:03.808 --> 53:05.602
Hold your ground!

53:05.643 --> 53:07.395
[dramatic music]

53:07.479 --> 53:09.606
- Front rank, kneel!

53:09.647 --> 53:12.525
♪ ♪

53:12.609 --> 53:14.152
- Ready!

53:14.194 --> 53:16.488
Aim!

53:16.529 --> 53:23.078
♪ ♪

53:23.161 --> 53:28.333
- Henderson, get your men back,
and take your son with you!

53:28.416 --> 53:30.001
- Why wait?
They've had their warning.

53:30.043 --> 53:31.670
Give the order.

53:31.753 --> 53:38.677
♪ ♪

53:43.598 --> 53:45.350
- Tell them to stand down.
- What?

53:45.392 --> 53:46.976
- Tell them.
- Don't weaken now!

53:47.018 --> 53:48.186
- Tell them!

53:48.269 --> 53:50.188
- Captain,
stand down the troops.

53:50.271 --> 53:53.066
- Company, recover!

53:53.149 --> 53:54.859
Front rank, stand!

53:54.901 --> 53:57.779
[strikers cheering]

53:57.862 --> 54:04.703
♪ ♪

54:04.786 --> 54:06.955
- What have you done?

54:07.038 --> 54:08.873
- How could I?

54:08.957 --> 54:10.792
These men have families.

54:10.875 --> 54:16.006
♪ ♪

54:16.047 --> 54:18.008
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:18.049 --> 54:19.551
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:19.592 --> 54:21.136
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:21.219 --> 54:22.554
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:22.595 --> 54:24.139
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:24.222 --> 54:25.390
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:25.473 --> 54:28.810
- Workmen!
strikers: Unite!

54:28.893 --> 54:31.771
[dramatic music]

54:31.855 --> 54:38.778
♪ ♪

55:39.506 --> 55:42.092
[bright tone]
